  abstract = {Background The net cooling effect of aerosols was supposed to mitigate warming brought by greenhouse gases (GHG). Huge uncertainties in aerosol composition and hygroscopicity lead to large uncertainties that obscure our understanding on (GHG) induce change. Fig 1: Best estimates scaling factors and their 5--95 percent confidence intervals Return Event Attribution We recorded a higher return period value under GHG compared to ALL. The return level occurs in the GHG-only simulations exceeding the natural-only threshold. Data Historical simulations from 1950-2014 from the Detection and Attribution Model Intercomparison Project are utilised. 12 multimodel ensemble mean of historicalALL, Greenhouse (GHG), Natural (NAT), and Aerosol (AER) and Anthropogenic (ANT) forcings. The East Asia region at latitude 20-50{$^\circ$}N longitude 100-145{$^\circ$}E and two sub-regions, including the Transitional climatic zone and the Humid East Asia Zone 20-35{$^\circ$}N longitude 105-120{$^\circ$}E are our focused. Method The Optimal fingerprint approach was employed. observed response Y was regressed to the multimodel (MME) response X, given by the equation below. Y denotes the observation, X denotes the multi-modeled ensemble simulated pattern, denotes the unknown scaling factor to be evaluated, and denotes internal climate variability. Fig 2: Return events for GHG and ALL forcing, event thresholds are defined from NAT The Atmospheric moisture budget is used to diagnose the underlying mechanism, which suggests vertical advection term primarily responsible for intensified precipitation during JJA. Conclusion Our results show signals from natural and anthropogenic factors are responsible for the observed amplified precipitation extreme},
